Edward de Bono</div>
</div>
</div>
<p><b>Edward de Bono</b> (born May 19, 1933, in <a href="/wiki/Malta" title="Malta">Malta</a>) is a <a href="/wiki/Maltese_people" title="Maltese people">Maltese</a> <a href="/wiki/Physician" title="Physician">physician</a>, <a href="/wiki/Author" title="Author">author</a>, <a href="/wiki/Inventor" title="Inventor">inventor</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Organizational_Psychology" title="Organizational Psychology" class="mw-redirect">consultant</a>. He is best known as the originator of the term <a href="/wiki/Lateral_thinking" title="Lateral thinking">lateral thinking</a> and a proponent of the deliberate teaching of thinking as a subject in schools.</p>
